1
00:00:00,030 --> 00:00:04,230
I'm&nbsp;Robb Gaff&nbsp;with the Professional Ski Instructors of America Alpine team.

2
00:00:04,230 --> 00:00:08,339
Maybe you're a beginner skier or maybe you've decided it's time to learn.

3
00:00:08,339 --> 00:00:19,827
In any case I'm teamed up here with REI to share some tips with you on how to make it the best experience possible. Here's how to ski.

4
00:00:19,827 --> 00:00:22,387
First you're gonna need to know how to put your gear on.

5
00:00:22,387 --> 00:00:27,319
We've made a video for that, check out the link below for the way to do that in the most easy way possible.

6
00:00:27,319 --> 00:00:38,932
Beyond that, we're gonna start to cover things like your basic stance you want to have while you're sliding on your skis and linking some wedge turns.

7
00:00:38,932 --> 00:00:43,591
Right now I'd like to talk about the stance you want to have while your skis are sliding down the hill.

8
00:00:43,591 --> 00:00:56,012
Essentially if you stand with your feet just a comfortable width apart, weight is equal on both feet and just give yourself a little jump in the air.

9
00:00:56,012 --> 00:00:59,629
The position that you land in is a pretty great skier stance.

10
00:00:59,629 --> 00:01:02,556
My shins are tilted forward, meaning my ankles are flexed.

11
00:01:02,556 --> 00:01:07,251
My arms are forward and out to the side so I can use them to help me balance.

12
00:01:07,251 --> 00:01:10,856
Similar to if I was gonna walk across a log over a stream.

13
00:01:10,856 --> 00:01:14,303
I'd want to carry my arms wide like this to help me with balance.

14
00:01:14,303 --> 00:01:20,981
That position, boom, shoulders a little bit in front of my hips.&nbsp; That's how I want to ski down the hill.

15
00:01:20,981 --> 00:01:26,515
So if I click into my skis again, repeat that little jump.

16
00:01:26,515 --> 00:01:35,882
Shins forward, hands out, shoulders in front of my hips, I'm good to go.

17
00:01:35,882 --> 00:01:41,032
[The Wedge] One of the first things you're gonna want to master while you're learning how to ski is making a wedge.

18
00:01:41,032 --> 00:01:44,390
Basically that means making a triangle shape with your skis.

19
00:01:44,390 --> 00:01:48,639
As we do that we just want to let our legs open up as we turn our toes in.

20
00:01:48,639 --> 00:01:53,117
Again to form a triangle shape. The bigger my triangle, the slower I'm gonna go.

21
00:01:53,117 --> 00:01:57,860
So it's gonna be important to practice kind of a smallish triangle as well as the biggest triangle.

22
00:01:57,860 --> 00:02:02,069
One way I like to do it again is just to jump up, legs open up, toes turn in.

23
00:02:02,069 --> 00:02:07,094
Do that from the side again, my same basic stance but in a triangle.

24
00:02:07,094 --> 00:02:18,365
If I put my skis on, I'm gonna let my legs open up, my knees relaxed out to the side and the toes turn in.

25
00:02:18,365 --> 00:02:20,684
Making a triangle shape with my skis.

26
00:02:20,684 --> 00:02:27,151
And again, if I just make a little bit of a triangle, I'll just control my skis and glide down the slope.

27
00:02:27,151 --> 00:02:32,872
If I open a little bit bigger into a bigger triangle, I'll actually stop myself, a braking wedge it's called.

28
00:02:32,872 --> 00:02:37,784
So if I slide up here to the top of the hill, get myself in a great basic stance.

29
00:02:37,784 --> 00:02:45,967
As I slide straight, little by little, nice and patiently, I slide my skis open into a triangle or what we call a wedge.

30
00:02:45,967 --> 00:02:48,340
Don't be afraid to do this a bunch of times.

31
00:02:48,340 --> 00:02:57,132
Mastering this wedge is really gonna build you up for success later on.

32
00:02:57,132 --> 00:03:07,432
[Walking Uphill] Once you feel comfortable moving around on the flats and your basic stance and making a wedge, now it's time to up the ante a little bit and figure out how to climb up the hill and come down a little bit more of a slope.

33
00:03:07,432 --> 00:03:09,094
So let's figure out how to do that together.

34
00:03:09,094 --> 00:03:13,613
One way to climb up the hill is to do what's called sidestepping.

35
00:03:13,613 --> 00:03:21,841
In order to sidestep, I've got to keep my skis parallel and take small steps, making sure they always stay sideways to the hill.

36
00:03:21,841 --> 00:03:32,416
Keeping that bottom ski tipped up on its side instead of on the bottom is gonna help me dig the edge of the ski in so I can push off of it and take nice small steps to get up the hill.

37
00:03:32,416 --> 00:03:36,805
So as I'm sidestepping up the hill, you can see the skinny little lines that my skis leave in the snow.

38
00:03:36,805 --> 00:03:40,996
That tells me that my ski is on its side and not flat on the bottom part.

39
00:03:40,996 --> 00:03:43,568
That'll get me up the hill every single time.

40
00:03:43,568 --> 00:03:47,679
Another way to walk up the hill, which is my favorite, is what's called herringboning.

41
00:03:47,679 --> 00:03:52,844
With a herringbone, I basically put my skis in a reverse triangle or reverse wedge position.

42
00:03:52,844 --> 00:03:56,914
The fronts of my skis are splayed way open and my legs are nice and wide open.

43
00:03:56,914 --> 00:04:06,384
I'll let my knees just kind of relax towards the inside so I can kind of use the edges of my skis a little bit to help me push up the hill.

44
00:04:06,384 --> 00:04:10,461
In order to do that, I've got to face up the hill.

45
00:04:10,461 --> 00:04:23,502
Again, as I herringbone, or a duck walk some people call it, you can see the skinny little lines from the edges of my skis as they sort of dig into the snow.

46
00:04:23,502 --> 00:04:30,786
So I feel like this slope is pretty good. It's just a little bit steeper than where I was gliding down practicing my first wedges.

47
00:04:30,786 --> 00:04:37,019
This is just a little bit steeper, but first of all I got to get myself turned around so that I'm in balance before I even start.

48
00:04:37,019 --> 00:04:40,564
In order to do that, teeny little steps, take your time.

49
00:04:40,564 --> 00:04:46,108
Take a thousand steps versus taking only a few steps and risk tripping yourself up.

50
00:04:46,108 --> 00:04:53,056
Little teeny steps. Once you get yourself about across the hill, go ahead and put yourself in a triangle.

51
00:04:53,056 --> 00:04:59,335
As you continue to step your skis around, that way before you even start to slide, you're in balance, you're in a triangle.

52
00:04:59,335 --> 00:05:01,481
Give yourself a little push.

53
00:05:01,481 --> 00:05:09,120
Again, that basic stance, opening up your skis into a triangle as you slide.

54
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:13,885
When it's time to stop, go ahead and increase the size of your triangle just a little bit.

55
00:05:13,885 --> 00:05:18,185
So again, the tendency is to walk up the hill too high as you're climbing up here.

56
00:05:18,185 --> 00:05:22,624
Make sure you take little small steps so that each time you come down you feel like you're in balance.

57
00:05:22,624 --> 00:05:33,769
As you keep practicing this over and over and over again, make sure you feel really comfortable before you move on to the next step.

58
00:05:33,769 --> 00:05:38,590
[Turning with the wedge] We know how to move around on the flats, climb up the hill, make a wedge going straight.

59
00:05:38,590 --> 00:05:42,482
Our next task is to figure out how to change direction.

60
00:05:42,482 --> 00:05:46,437
So we're gonna get ourselves pointed down the hill.

61
00:05:46,437 --> 00:05:51,992
A little bit of a triangle, not so big necessarily. And it's gonna steer my skis over to one side.

62
00:05:51,992 --> 00:05:54,235
Keeping in a triangle the entire time.

63
00:05:54,235 --> 00:06:00,632
I basically use the movement of turning my thighs, turning my legs, twisting my legs to steer my wedge over to one side.

64
00:06:00,632 --> 00:06:08,311
Similarly to how you might steer your car throughout a turn or steer a bicycle throughout a turn, it's the same concept.

65
00:06:08,311 --> 00:06:16,760
But I've got to use this twisting movement of my thighs and legs and feet to get the triangle to turn over to one side.

66
00:06:16,760 --> 00:06:22,351
It's okay, as you're making a direction change, to allow a little bit more weight to go to one ski.

67
00:06:22,351 --> 00:06:26,897
But mostly we want to concentrate on turning the legs, turning the legs, steering the skis.

68
00:06:26,897 --> 00:06:28,502
a little bit more weight, maybe&nbsp;

69
00:06:28,502 --> 00:06:32,296
So from turning to the right, it's okay to have a teeny bit more weight on my left ski.

70
00:06:32,296 --> 00:06:36,020
From turning to the left, it's okay to have a teeny bit more weight on the right ski.

71
00:06:36,020 --> 00:06:39,349
But I don't want to worry about having big movement side to side with my body.

72
00:06:39,349 --> 00:06:41,744
Stay balanced, steer your skis by turning your legs.

73
00:06:41,744 --> 00:06:43,901
Here's what it looks like.

74
00:06:43,901 --> 00:06:48,097
Again, a little bit of a triangle, nice basic balance stance.

75
00:06:48,097 --> 00:06:51,513
Use my legs to twist my skis over to the side.

76
00:06:51,513 --> 00:06:53,064
Steer that triangle.

77
00:06:53,064 --> 00:06:55,652
A little teeny bit more weight on that left ski.

78
00:06:55,652 --> 00:06:57,713
There's a direction change for you.

79
00:06:57,713 --> 00:06:59,894
Really important to try that.

80
00:06:59,894 --> 00:07:01,732
Don't worry about making a really huge turn.

81
00:07:01,732 --> 00:07:05,000
Just a little deviation from a straight line is a great place to start.

82
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,233
Practice it to the right a bunch, practice it to the left a bunch.

83
00:07:08,233 --> 00:07:10,059
Keep climbing up again.

84
00:07:10,059 --> 00:07:12,134
Get really good at this.

85
00:07:12,134 --> 00:07:16,139
All right, so here's what it looks like to make a turn to the left.

86
00:07:16,139 --> 00:07:20,275
A bit of a triangle, twist those legs to steer those skis.

87
00:07:20,275 --> 00:07:28,879
Little teeny bit more weight on this right ski. Boom.

88
00:07:28,879 --> 00:07:31,512
[Linking Wedge Turns] Now is when it really starts to become fun.

89
00:07:31,512 --> 00:07:34,321
We're gonna try to link together some wedge turns.

90
00:07:34,321 --> 00:07:47,153
So while I'm doing that, I'm gonna let my skis steer them over to one side and then kind of take a second and be in almost a neutral stance, gliding straight for a little bit before I start to twist and steer my skis back to the other side.

91
00:07:47,153 --> 00:07:53,282
Again, what's important is not being in a hurry, not trying to make really sharp turns, and staying in the triangle.

92
00:07:53,282 --> 00:07:54,899
Looks something like this.

93
00:07:54,899 --> 00:07:58,388
Again, making sure I'm in a triangle, great basic stance.

94
00:07:58,388 --> 00:08:02,281
Steer my skis by twisting my legs.

95
00:08:02,281 --> 00:08:03,538
Neutral spot again.

96
00:08:03,538 --> 00:08:04,790
Making sure I'm in a triangle.

97
00:08:04,790 --> 00:08:09,657
Twist my legs, steer my triangle over to the side.

98
00:08:09,657 --> 00:08:11,749
Teeny bit more weight on this left ski.

99
00:08:11,749 --> 00:08:14,583
Back into a neutral position again.

100
00:08:14,583 --> 00:08:17,149
Start to twist my legs in the opposite direction.

101
00:08:17,149 --> 00:08:19,417
A little bit more weight on this right ski.

102
00:08:19,417 --> 00:08:24,377
Keep my basic stance with my shins tilted forwards.

103
00:08:24,377 --> 00:08:34,671
Each time I want to make a turn, I'm patient, twist both legs to steer my wedge, to steer that triangle.

104
00:08:34,671 --> 00:08:38,740
Feel those skis just gliding over the snow.

105
00:08:38,740 --> 00:08:46,653
If you need to slow down a little bit, just scoop that turn a little bit more up the hill.

106
00:08:46,653 --> 00:08:50,475
Linking wedge turns, that's skiing and that's fun.

107
00:08:50,475 --> 00:08:58,601
With those skills you have right now of being able to control your speed by making wedge turns, you're gonna be able to ski on any green run any place in the world, any mountain.

108
00:08:58,601 --> 00:09:05,955
Take note, as I was making those turns, I was letting my skis come across the hill to control my speed and not making a big triangle.

109
00:09:05,955 --> 00:09:08,866
Keep that in mind as you practice and practice and practice.

110
00:09:08,866 --> 00:09:10,394
You can't do enough of those.

111
00:09:10,394 --> 00:09:13,425
The more you practice, the better you'll get and the more fun you're gonna have.

112
00:09:13,425 --> 00:09:18,107
The Professional Ski Instructors of America and REI hope you come out and take a lesson.

113
00:09:18,107 --> 00:09:20,607
Look forward to seeing you out there.

